IMF Needs More Lagarde
Davos — Lagarde has said she is open to serving another five years as head of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should stay.
The IMF has never had a better leader than her, and the IMF Board should give her the opportunity to complete the work she started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, inheriting an institution in crisis.
The 2008 global financial crash and its economic aftermath damaged the credibility of Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free-market "Washington Consensus."
Lagarde's leadership has helped the IMF restore its reputation.
Many have focused on her personal qualities — rightly so.
She is honest, strong, warm, and compelling.
Officials from various countries (often meeting in delicate situations) have consistently praised her for being brave enough to speak the difficult truths while also being a sensitive listener.
These are important qualities for a leader of an institution that must negotiate the terms of agreements rather than dominate them.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed to be restructured, or else firewalls had to be established to prevent financial contagion. It was harsh advice, but Europeans followed it.
Similarly, she strongly advocated for providing IMF support to certain countries — such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which was crucial for global stability.
There are countless more examples.
The IMF is not known for innovation, and usually lacks passion.
Lagarde began to change this.
In the process, she gave this institution, which often prescribed harsh remedies, a more humane face.
For example, managing the Middle East refugee crisis was originally outside the IMF's mandate.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its programs to allow the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to assist people displaced by the conflicts in Syria and Iraq (over one million people live in refugee camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak hit West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF to use available funds to provide debt relief to affected countries, enabling them to improve the pay for doctors and nurses — this was the first time the IMF used its capital in this way.
Furthermore, Lagarde recognizes that the world today faces three of the most important challenges and has taken action against them.
First, she strongly advocates for more women to join the workforce, and she herself serves as a role model demonstrating the value of women in leadership positions.
In a variety of countries, from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop wasting such a huge human resource — and thus realize their economic potential.
Second, under her leadership, the IMF has also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a basic issue of fairness.
IMF's research emphasizes a direct link between reducing income inequality and boosting economic growth.
IMF is not the first institution to demonstrate this, but its position makes the issue more prominent and urgent.
Lagarde has personally been committed to promoting this point, which is key to increasing its urgency.
Third, Lagarde has played an important role in helping the world recognize the full impact of technological change — some of which will have frighteningly disruptive effects.
For example, automation will continue to increase efficiency in manufacturing and reduce its costs, but it also means that the number of jobs generated by economic growth will be less than before.
The political, economic, and social consequences of this emerging reality are worth our recognition and serious study.
Lagarde has made the IMF the core of this effort.
Critics would say it is time for representatives from developing countries to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th European to hold this position in a row, and Europe's such privilege is difficult to justify in today's world.
Others would also say that the austerity measures supported by the IMF in Greece have not yielded significant results, proving that she has become disconnected from the general public.
Others will point out that she faces allegations linked to financial scandals in France, which would distract her from her work at the IMF.
After her predecessor, Dominique Strauss-Kahn, was deeply involved in a scandal, critics argue that the IMF must never again be distracted by similar events.
Let us analyze these objections one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside Europe and the United States.
But the goal of ending this Western privilege is to make the leader selection process based on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best candidate for IMF Managing Director, as the emerging powers such as the BRIC countries (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) did not jointly propose an alternative candidate.
Having a European serve as IMF Managing Director may also have been one of the favorable factors behind the IMF's decision late last year to include the renminbi in the currency basket that determines the value of its special drawing rights.
Furthermore, Lagarde, with impressive political flexibility, ultimately convinced both the Republican and Democratic parties in the US Congress to approve IMF governance reforms, which not only enhanced the IMF's arsenal to counter financial crises, but also more accurately reflected the changing dynamics of the global economy.
For example, the BRIC countries are now among the top ten shareholders of the IMF.
On the Greek issue, Lagarde made some direct — and some would say inappropriate — comments with a personal style last year.
But she is certainly not the culprit who brought economic suffering to the Greeks. Her tenure at the IMF fully demonstrates that no IMF Managing Director in history has done as much as she has to lead the IMF in efforts to alleviate the suffering of people in crisis.
Finally, the charges against Lagarde in France were opposed by the French chief prosecutor, and Lagarde was at most only slightly involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has proven that she is exactly such a leader, committed to adapting the IMF for the 21st century.
She deserves the opportunity to see her work through from start to finish.
